Ok, hardware transform and lighting.... <br>
<br>
Do you remember geometry class?  Think of a grid that has a third dimension of depth.  This is your world (world view)<br>
<br>
Now lets say you want to put a cube in it that you can rotate and do interesting stuff with.  So you create a second 3d grid with your cube in the center.  This cube has to go in the center so you can rotate it.  Things that need rotated have to be in the center of there grid.  <br>
<br>
Now lets say you want to put this cube rotated 90 degrees into your world.  You need to first rotate it in its own grid.  Then you need to move it into the world view.<br>
<br>
I am over simplifying it... but that is transforming.<br>
<br>
Lighting is simply lighting the vertices (again, making this simple) to make thinks look... lit up.<br>
<br>
Doing these 2 steps on the video card (a geforce has more transisters than a pentium 4!) is of great advantage because it was desiged for that rather than a pentium which is designed to do any number of things.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, the main difference between geforce 2/3 is that geforce 3 is faster and it allows you to program per pixel shaders.  I would be surprised if sol uses this technology as it is pretty new... we will see.<br>
